2) Normalization to 13674 reads per sample

Lets normalize the original dataset by randomly subsampling 13674 reads in each station:

library(vegan)
tb10_mitags_t<-t(tb10_mitags)
otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674<-rrarefy(tb10_mitags_t, 13674)

The normalized table shows the following dimensions and format:

## [1]    10 44069
##        OTU_1 OTU_2 OTU_3 OTU_4 OTU_5
## MP0311     0     0     0     1     1
## MP0528     2     0     0     8     0
## MP0778     0     0     0     0     0
## MP1176     0     0     0     0     1
## MP1421     0     0     0     0     0

Its content fits with the expected normalization values (13674 reads per station):

rowSums(otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674)
## MP0311 MP0528 MP0778 MP1176 MP1421 MP1517 MP1672 MP1857 MP2243 MP2821 
##  13674  13674  13674  13674  13674  13674  13674  13674  13674  13674

Lets check out how many OTUs dont appear in the new table:

length(which(colSums(otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674)==0)) 
## [1] 37829

There are 37810 OTUs that dont show any occurrence in the normalized data. Lets remove them from the table and take a look at its final dimensions:

otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674_no_cero<-otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674[,-(which(colSums(otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674)==0))]
dim(otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674_no_cero)
## [1]   10 6240

Datasets summary:

tb10_mitags_t > 10 1178

otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674_no_cero > 10 591

3) General community analysis

3.1) Richness and evenness (Shannon index)

Most of the samples take Shannon Index values between 2.25 and 3.25:

3.2) Richness: OTU number

Lowest number of OTUs per sample:

## [1] 1889

Maximum number of OTUs per sample:

## [1] 2431

In most of the samples, we can identify between 200 and 230 OTUs:

plot(sort(OTUs_per_sample_10_ss13674), pch=19)

boxplot(OTUs_per_sample_10_ss13674, pch=19)

3.3) Index of evenness

3.3.1) Pielous index

pielou_evenness_10_ss13674 <- otu_tb10_mitags_ss13674_div/log(OTUs_per_sample_10_ss13674)

The Pielou index (constrained between 0 and 1) takes values closer to 1 as the variation of species proportion in a sample decreases. Most of our samples get values between 0.425 and 0.625, meaning that the numerical composition of different OTUs within our samples is relatively similar:

plot(sort(pielou_evenness_10_ss13674), pch=19)

boxplot(pielou_evenness_10_ss13674, pch=19)

The OTU_1, with 20053 reads, is the most abundant in the overall dataset:

head(sort(colSums(otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674_no_cero), decreasing=T), n=10L)
## OTU_3009 OTU_2241 OTU_2660 OTU_5191  OTU_836  OTU_321 OTU_5093  OTU_145 
##     3368     2330     1731     1577     1452     1419     1346     1178 
## OTU_5172 OTU_1499 
##     1126     1089

Most of the OTUs show few occurrences, but we dont observe the presence of a massive group of rare OTUs:

plot(log(sort(colSums(otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674_no_cero), decreasing=T)), pch=19)

3.4) Abundance Models

3.4.1) Rank-Abundance or Dominance/Diversity Model (radfit)

The OTUs abundance distribution fits relativelly close to log-normal model.

3.4.2) Prestons Lognormal Model

According to Prestons lognormal model fit into species frequencies groups, were missing ~130 species:

otu_tb10_mitags_min13674_prestonfit<-prestonfit(colSums(tb10_mitags_t))
plot(otu_tb10_mitags_min13674_prestonfit, main="Pooled species")

veiledspec(otu_tb10_mitags_min13674_prestonfit)
## Extrapolated     Observed       Veiled 
##    14973.391     8173.000     6800.391

When computing Prestons lognormal model fit without pooling data into groups, we seem to miss ~118 species:

## Extrapolated     Observed       Veiled 
##    13554.538     8173.000     5381.538

3.6) Beta diversity

3.6.1) Dissimilarity matrix using Bray-Curtis index:

The Bray-Curtis dissimilarity, constrained between 0 (minimum distance) and 1 (highest dissimilarity) allows us to quantify the differences between samples according to the composition and relative abundance of their OTUs. In our dataset, most of the samples pairs take dissimilarity values between 0.35 and 0.55, meaning that their composition is quiet similar.

3.6.2) Hierarchical clustering

The only relatively evident clusters we can distinguish in the dendogram stand out in the very left side of the plot.

(To be done: assign Longhurst provinces information to each station and check if any of the central clusters is meaningful regarding to the samples geographical ubication)

3.6.3) Non-metric multidimensional scaling

We can identify a prominent group in the middle-left side of the NMDS and a few isolated samples in the right edge of the plot. Considering the overall distribution, were not able to identify any informative clustering pattern.

The stress parameter takes a value below 0.3, meaning that the plot is valid.

4.1) Mantel correlograms

When implementing the Mantel Test, we obtain a very low statistic, meaning that the correlation between samples dissimilarity and geographical distances is weak; besides, it is not significant, so we shouldnt consider the test meaningful.

mantel(geo_distances_MP_10_ss13674, otu_tb10_mitags_t_ss13674_no_cero.bray)
